    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-01T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-01T15:00:00-05:00" n="525"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115/20497: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at London</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-01T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 1, 1919—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your November 26, 6 p.m. Department believes deposits to effect release of goods
                    detained under Order in Council of March 11, 1915, should be released in proper
                    cases without further delay as economic <pb facs="0722" n="632" xml:id="pg_632"
                    /> reasons for detention of goods ceased long ago. Ambassador has taken up
                    matter of release of these deposits with Foreign Office, but as yet no reply has
                    been received. Department desires to obtain list of these cases and amount
                    deposited in each case and total amount involved. Telegraph report.<note n="34"
                        xml:id="d525fn34">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
